        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-800 text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Star Wheel &#x26; <span class="text-accent-bright">Timing Screw</span> Conveyors
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ AIO DEFINITION ═══ -->
  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          Star wheel conveyors and timing screws (worm screws) use rotating helical screws and pocketed wheels to space, time, and transfer round containers , bottles, cans, and jars , at precise intervals into rotary filling, capping, and labeling machines. The timing screw separates a continuous stream of touching containers into individually spaced units, and the star wheel captures each container and places it into a machine station synchronized to the machine's rotational speed. Star wheel and timing screw infeed systems serve beverage, food, pharmaceutical, and personal care packaging lines at speeds from 50 to 2,000+ containers per minute.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ HOW STAR WHEELS WORK ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">The Function</div>
        <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          How Star Wheels <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            A star wheel is a rotating disc with evenly spaced semicircular pockets around its perimeter. Each pocket is sized to receive one container. The star wheel rotates in synchronization with the rotary machine it feeds , one pocket per machine station. As the star wheel turns, each pocket captures a container from the infeed conveyor and guides it into the corresponding machine station (a filler valve, a capper chuck, a labeling station). On the outfeed side, a second star wheel extracts each container from the machine station and transfers it onto the discharge conveyor.
          </p>
          <p>
            Star wheels function as the bridge between linear conveyor flow and rotary machine motion. Containers arrive on a flat conveyor in single file. The <a href="/conveyor-functions/infeed-outfeed/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">infeed</a> star wheel converts that linear stream into rotary motion by capturing containers into its pockets. The outfeed star wheel converts rotary motion back to linear flow. Without star wheels, there is no way to transfer containers between a linear conveyor and a rotary machine at production speeds.
          </p>
          <p>
            Star wheel pocket geometry must match the container diameter precisely. A pocket too large allows the container to shift and arrive at the machine station off-center. A pocket too small jams the container or damages the container wall. Pocket diameter tolerance is typically ±0.5 mm for glass containers and ±1.0 mm for plastic containers. This tight tolerance is why star wheels are container-specific change parts , a different container diameter requires a different star wheel.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ TIMING SCREWS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="screw-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Timing Screws</div>
        <h2 id="screw-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Timing Screws &#x26; <span class="text-accent">Worm Screws</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">How Timing Screws Separate Containers</h3>
          <p>
            A timing screw is a rotating helical screw mounted horizontally alongside the infeed conveyor, parallel to the direction of container travel. Containers arrive touching (zero gap) on the infeed belt. The screw's helix engages each container in sequence, and because the screw's pitch (the distance between adjacent helix flights) increases from the infeed end to the discharge end, each container is progressively separated from the one behind it.
          </p>
          <p>
            At the screw's infeed end, the pitch matches the container diameter , containers fit snugly between adjacent flights with zero gap. As the screw turns and the container advances, the widening pitch creates a growing gap behind each container. At the discharge end, the pitch matches the star wheel's pocket spacing (the machine's station pitch). The container exits the screw at the exact spacing and timing needed for the star wheel to capture it.
          </p>
          <p>
            This progressive spacing function is critical for <a href="/conveyor-functions/metering/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">metering</a> containers into high-speed rotary machines. Without the timing screw, containers would arrive at the star wheel in an uncontrolled mass, causing jams, double-feeds, and missed stations. The timing screw guarantees one container per star wheel pocket at the correct arrival time.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Single vs. Dual Timing Screws</h3>
          <p>
            Single-screw systems use one helical screw on one side of the conveyor with a guide rail on the opposite side. The screw contacts the container on one side and the guide rail constrains the other side. Single screws handle stable, round containers (PET bottles, aluminum cans, glass jars) at moderate speeds. They are the most common configuration for lines running up to <!-- VERIFY: 300-400 containers per minute typical single-screw limit --> 400 containers per minute.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dual-screw systems use two timing screws , one on each side of the conveyor , rotating in opposite directions. Both screws contact the container simultaneously, centering it precisely and eliminating the lateral force that single screws impart. Dual screws handle unstable containers (tall, narrow bottles with high center of gravity), lightweight containers that tip easily, and high-speed lines running 400-1,200+ containers per minute. Dual screws also improve <a href="/conveyor-functions/singulation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">singulation</a> accuracy because both sides of the container are positively controlled.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Pitch and Spacing Control</h3>
          <p>
            The timing screw's pitch profile is the core engineering parameter. Pitch at the infeed end equals container diameter (touching containers). Pitch at the discharge end equals machine station spacing (star wheel pocket pitch). The pitch transition between these two values determines the acceleration profile each container experiences as it separates from the stream.
          </p>
          <p>
            Linear pitch profiles (constant pitch increase per revolution) produce constant container acceleration , simple to manufacture but can cause container instability at high speeds due to sudden engagement. Sinusoidal and polynomial pitch profiles (variable pitch increase) produce smoother acceleration and deceleration curves that reduce container tipping and scuffing. High-speed beverage lines (600+ BPM) universally use computed pitch profiles optimized for the specific container's center of gravity, coefficient of friction, and line speed.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ CHANGEOVER ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="changeover-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Changeover</div>
        <h2 id="changeover-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Change Parts &#x26; <span class="text-accent">Changeover</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Star wheels and timing screws are inherently container-specific. Each container diameter, height, and shape requires a matched set of change parts: the timing screw itself, the infeed star wheel, the outfeed star wheel, guide rails, and wear plates. A packaging line running five container sizes needs five complete change part sets. Change parts represent a significant capital and inventory cost , timing screws alone cost $$ per screw, and a full change part set (screws plus star wheels plus guides) for one container size on a high-speed rotary filler can approach the $$ range.
          </p>
          <p>
            Manual changeover involves removing the current screw and star wheels (typically held by one or two bolts and a locating pin), installing the new set, and adjusting guide rail positions. Skilled operators complete manual changeover in 15-30 minutes. Tool-less quick-change systems use cam-lock mounts, color-coded locating pins, and captive fasteners to reduce changeover to 2-5 minutes without tools.
          </p>
          <p>
            Servo-driven adjustable timing screws eliminate some change parts by using programmable pitch profiles. Instead of swapping the physical screw, the servo changes the screw's speed profile to accommodate different container diameters. These systems reduce the change part inventory but cannot handle extreme diameter differences , the screw's physical helix still has a fixed geometry. Servo adjustment works within a container diameter range (e.g., 50-80 mm) but requires a physical screw change outside that range.
          </p>
          <p>
            For lines running in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/beverage/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">beverage</a> and <a href="/industries/pharmaceutical-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pharmaceutical</a> environments, change parts must be stored in labeled racks or carts to prevent damage, contamination, and mix-ups. Timing screws are precision-machined components , dropping a screw or storing it loosely against other metal parts causes dings in the helix flight edges that create container handling problems (scuffing, jamming, inconsistent spacing).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SYNCHRONIZATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="sync-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Synchronization</div>
        <h2 id="sync-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Machine <span class="text-accent">Synchronization</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            The timing screw and star wheel must rotate in exact synchronization with the rotary machine. If the screw delivers a container 5 milliseconds early, the star wheel pocket is not in position to receive it , the container crashes into the star wheel's land area (the solid section between pockets). If 5 milliseconds late, the pocket passes empty and the machine station runs without a container, causing a missed fill or an empty station that disrupts downstream operations.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Mechanical Synchronization</h3>
          <p>
            Traditional systems use a mechanical gear train or timing belt connecting the timing screw shaft, star wheel shaft, and machine main shaft. All three rotate at fixed ratios , the timing screw makes one revolution for every N containers (where N equals the number of helix starts), and the star wheel makes one revolution for every M containers (where M equals the number of pockets). Mechanical synchronization is inherently precise because the physical gear connection prevents any timing drift. The disadvantage is inflexibility , speed ratio changes require gear changes, and the entire system must start and stop together.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Electronic (Servo) Synchronization</h3>
          <p>
            Modern systems replace mechanical gearing with servo motors on the timing screw and star wheel, electronically synchronized to the machine's main encoder via electronic cam profiles in the PLC or motion controller. Servo synchronization allows real-time speed adjustment, soft-start acceleration ramps (preventing container tipping during startup), and programmable position offsets for fine-tuning container placement. Current servo platforms provide sub-millisecond synchronization accuracy using EtherNet/IP, PROFINET, or EtherCAT fieldbus protocols.
          </p>
          <p>
            Electronic synchronization enables features impossible with mechanical gearing: automatic speed matching during production rate changes, controlled deceleration during machine faults (preventing container pile-ups), and recipe-based changeover where the PLC loads different cam profiles for different container sizes without mechanical adjustment.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ CONTAINER HANDLING ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="container-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Container Handling</div>
        <h2 id="container-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Container <span class="text-accent">Handling</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Star wheels and timing screws handle round containers exclusively. Non-round containers (square bottles, rectangular cartons, irregular shapes) cannot engage with a helical screw profile and will jam. For non-round container infeed, packaging lines use servo-driven bucket conveyors, lug chains, or indexing belt systems instead of timing screws.
          </p>
          <p>
            Container material affects timing screw design. Glass containers are heavy and rigid , they tolerate moderate screw contact pressure without deformation but can chip or crack from impact. PET bottles are light and flexible , they deform under excessive screw pressure, causing inconsistent spacing. Aluminum cans are thin-walled and easily dented , timing screws for cans use UHMW or Delrin helix flights instead of stainless steel to prevent denting.
          </p>
          <p>
            Container stability is the primary constraint on line speed. Tall, narrow containers with high centers of gravity tip at lower speeds than short, wide containers. The timing screw's acceleration profile, guide rail height, and conveyor belt friction coefficient must all support the container's stability at the target line speed. Lightweight empty PET bottles are the most challenging , they blow over from air currents, tip from minor vibrations, and float on wet conveyors. Beverage lines filling empty bottles often run the infeed section at lower speed and increase speed after filling adds weight and stability.
          </p>
          <p>
            Pocket spacing on star wheels determines the minimum container-to-container gap at the machine. Standard star wheel designs use equal-pitch pockets , every pocket is the same size and spacing. Variable-pitch star wheels (used on some labeling and inspection machines) use alternating large and small pockets to handle containers of different diameters without changing the star wheel.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ APPLICATIONS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="applications-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
        <h2 id="applications-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Industry <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Beverage Filling Lines</h3>
          <p>
            Beverage lines are the largest application for star wheel and timing screw systems. High-speed rotary fillers run at 200 to 2,000+ bottles per minute. At these speeds, timing screw precision is non-negotiable , a 1,200 BPM filler with 60 filling valves requires containers delivered at 50-millisecond intervals with sub-millimeter positioning accuracy. Multi-start timing screws (two or three helical flights on one screw) increase throughput without increasing screw RPM.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Pharmaceutical Bottle Lines</h3>
          <p>
            Pharmaceutical bottle lines run at lower speeds (50-300 BPM) but demand higher precision and regulatory compliance. Timing screws and star wheels in pharmaceutical applications use 316L stainless steel construction, sanitary surface finishes (32 Ra or better), and tool-less disassembly for cleaning validation. Container tracking through the star wheel zone must maintain serialization integrity , every bottle must arrive at the correct filler station in the correct sequence for track-and-trace compliance.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Capping and Labeling Machine Infeed</h3>
          <p>
            Rotary cappers and rotary labelers use star wheels identically to fillers. The timing screw spaces containers and the star wheel places them into capper chucks or labeler stations. Capping star wheels must position the container directly under the cap delivery chute , misalignment by even 2-3 mm causes cross-threaded caps or missed cap placement. Labeling star wheels must position the container at a consistent rotational orientation for label registration, often using a container orientation device (spinner cup or friction belt) integrated into the star wheel transfer zone.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ RELATED ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-ink-light" aria-labelledby="related-heading">
      <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
